            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 3-year-old girl who appears tired and clingy, sitting quietly in her mother’s lap and becoming irritable when examined. She has a flushed face, intermittent coughing spells, and breathes faster than expected for her age, with mild subcostal retractions during periods of fever. Her appetite has dropped over the last several days, and her parents report that she has been drinking less than usual but still produces wet diapers or urinates several times a day. She is small but well nourished, dressed appropriately for the season, and developmentally active at baseline.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is usually energetic, talkative, and curious. She enjoys picture books, stacking blocks, pretend play with stuffed animals, and short playground outings when well. She attends daycare during the week, where several children recently had colds. Her family lives in a smoke-free apartment, and both parents are attentive and engaged in her care. She has a close relationship with an older brother and is often around grandparents who help with childcare.\n\nOver the past 4 days, {patientName} developed rhinorrhea and a dry cough that progressed to fever, worsening cough, and reduced activity. In the last 24 hours, her parents noticed faster breathing, poor sleep, and that she wanted to be held more often. They deny choking, foreign-body aspiration, or recent travel. There has been no cyanosis, but she appears uncomfortable and less playful than usual.\n\nHer social setting is typical for a preschool child. She does not take part in organized sports but is physically active in normal play. Immunizations are mostly up to date, though her seasonal influenza vaccine was missed this year. Her diet is somewhat selective, favoring pasta, fruit, yogurt, and crackers, and she drinks water and milk regularly when healthy. She has strong family support, and her parents are reliable historians who sought care promptly when her breathing became more labored."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f567b159-476f-41b6-8961-a468dfee7e85",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at term without major perinatal complications and has met developmental milestones appropriately. She has no known chronic cardiopulmonary disease and no previous diagnosis of asthma. Her past medical history is notable only for common viral upper respiratory infections associated with daycare attendance and one prior episode of acute otitis media treated successfully as an outpatient. She has never been hospitalized and has no history of intensive care admission.\n\nAccording to her parents, {patientName} became ill 4 days ago with nasal congestion and low-grade fever, followed by worsening cough and higher fevers up to 39.3 C at home. Over the last day she has had decreased appetite, lower fluid intake, and increased fatigue. Her parents noticed faster breathing and mild chest indrawing, prompting evaluation. There is no history of seizure, rash, known aspiration event, chronic swallowing difficulty, or underlying immunodeficiency.\n\nShe lives with her parents and older brother, attends daycare, and has frequent exposure to other children with respiratory illnesses. There is no household tobacco exposure, no pets at home, and no known mold exposure. She uses an age-appropriate car seat, sleeps in her own bed, and receives routine pediatric care. Immunizations are current except for the most recent seasonal influenza vaccine. She is not on chronic prescription medications."
          }
        ]
